### Function to Plot j and f vs Reynolds Number

```matlab
function plotJandFvsRe(xOptimal)
    % Define the range of Reynolds numbers (Re) to plot
    Re_values = linspace(300, 15000, 100); % For example, 100 points between 300 and 15000

    % Initialize vectors to store j and f values
    j_values = zeros(length(Re_values), 1);
    f_values = zeros(length(Re_values), 1);

    % Loop over the range of Re values to calculate j and f
    for i = 1:length(Re_values)
        current_Re = Re_values(i);
        j_values(i) = ColburnFactor(xOptimal(1), xOptimal(2), xOptimal(3), xOptimal(4), current_Re);
        f_values(i) = FrictionFactor(xOptimal(1), xOptimal(2), xOptimal(3), xOptimal(4), current_Re);
    end

    % Now create the plots
    figure;
    subplot(2, 1, 1);
    plot(Re_values, j_values, 'b-');
    xlabel('Reynolds Number (Re)');
    ylabel('Colburn Factor (j)');
    title('Colburn Factor (j) vs. Reynolds Number');

    subplot(2, 1, 2);
    plot(Re_values, f_values, 'r-');
    xlabel('Reynolds Number (Re)');
    ylabel('Friction Factor (f)');
    title('Friction Factor (f) vs. Reynolds Number');
